Thorax.
Prothorax black with a hardly noticeable metallic-green lustre and yellowish ventral margins; ventral parts of anterior margin of anterior lobe also narrowly outlined with yellowish colour (
Fig. 4a
). Mesostigmal plate black dorsally (including anterior triangle), pale at sides, its anterior projections pale but outlined with black (
Fig. 4a
).

In living specimens, the ventral part of mesepimeron and the black parts of metepisternum and metepimeron are covered with a strong pruinescence while the dorsal part of mesepimeron remains free from it and is saturated black; the mesinfraepisternus and metinfraepisternum are also variably pruinosed (
Fig. 2
). The elongate black spots at posterior 2/3 of interpleural suture and at anterior part of metepimeron lower margin are not pruinosed and very conspicuous in living specimens (
Fig. 2
). This pruinescence is mostly washed out by acetone and its amount left in dead specimens is variable (
Fig. 5
), an artifact of acetone treatment.

Wings (
Fig. 4g
) hyaline; venation blackish-brown. Pterostigmata blackish brown with bordering longitudinal veins black, cover two underlying cells, 2.8 times as long as high; its costal side slightly convex. Px 10 (1 case), 11 (12 cases) or 12 (3 cases) in FW, 9 (3 cases), 10 (7 cases), 11 (5 cases) or 12 (1 case) in HW. CuP situated midway between antenodals, Ac at the second antenodal. IR 2 becomes more or less angulated at level of RP 2 origin. Origins of IR 2 and RP 3+4 separated a bit more than length of the first crossvein between them. Two intercalar sectors between IR 2 and RP 3+4 and between RP 3+4 and MA.

Cerci strongly bent inwards and slightly below at distal 1/3; their tips rounded (and very slightly expanding) and touching each other (
Fig. 4d, f
). Each cercus with a broad subbasal inner tooth as a skewed triangle at ¼ of cercus length, followed by an inner long trapezoid projection, with margin almost even, without obvious teeth but just coarse (
Fig. 4d, f
). These inner structures are scarcely seen in lateral view (
Fig. 4e
). Cercus yellowish with blackish brown base and subbasal tooth and black apices, border of colours indistinct; inner margin of trapezoid projection very narrowly outlined with brownish. Paraprocts long, ca 45% as long as cerci in dorsal view (
Fig. 4d
) and ca 55% in ventral view (
Fig. 4f
). Each paraproct broad in basal half, then incised at inner side before a blunt triangular inner projection, subapical inner sides truncated at ca 45 
o
to body axis, apices rounded (
Fig. 4
c–d, f). In two specimens, including the illustrated one (
Fig. 4
), the inner projections of the two cerci touch each other so that the incisions of both paraprocts form an arrowhead shape (
Fig. 4
c–d, f). In eight specimens, the paraprocts are set a bit more apart so that their inner subapical projections do not touch each other, but their shape including the asymmetrical blunt triangular shape of the incision between them and the basal projection, are the same. Expanded flat apical parts of two paraprocts are not in the same plane but are oriented somewhat in a roof-like manner.

